The '''Hero's Medal''' ({{zh|s=<U+82F1><U+96C4><U+6A21><U+8303><U+5956><U+7AE0>|p=Y<U+012B>ng Xi<U+00F3>ng M<U+00F3> F<U+00E0>n Ji<U+01CE>ng Zh<U+0101>ng}}) is currently the highest [[military decoration]] awarded by the [[Government of the People's Republic of China]].<ref name=xinhua/><ref name=regulation/>

==History==

The Hero's Medal, along with the [[Meritorious Service Medal (China)|Meritorious Service Medal]], was first created in April 1951 by the Chinese [[People's Volunteer Army]] political director Du Ping in an effort to promote the unity of the Chinese armed forces during the [[Korean War]].<ref name=zhang197>{{harvnb|Zhang|1995|p=197}}.</ref> The medal was conceived so that the common soldiers would follow the examples set by few selected role models.<ref name=zhang197/> When the medal was first created, it was composed of three categories <U+2014> second, first and special class.<ref name=zhang197/> The special class was later eliminated when the Chinese [[People's Liberation Army]]'s (PLA) medal system formalized in 1988.<ref name=xinhua>{{zh icon}}{{cite | url = http://news.xinhuanet.com/mil/2007-07/05/content_6333702.htm | title = 80th Anniversary of the Birth of the Armed Forces: Introduction to Service and Award Medals (<U+5EFA><U+519B>80<U+5468><U+5E74><U+FF1A><U+52CB><U+7AE0><U+3001><U+5956><U+7AE0> <U+95EA><U+8000><U+5728><U+519B><U+4EBA><U+80F8><U+524D><U+7684><U+8363><U+8000>) | date = 2007-07-05 |publisher = Xinhua | location = Beijing, China| accessdate = 2010-10-06}}</ref>

==Criteria and selection process==

According to the initial award criteria published in 1951, the medal was awarded to anyone "who have owned two medals of third or second class or one of the first grade [Meritorious Service] award, who are most outstanding at an army or army corps level,<ref>In Chinese military nomenclature, the term "Army" (<U+519B>) means [[Corps]], while the term "Army Corps" (<U+5175><U+56E2>) means [[Field Army|Army]].</ref> and whose remarkable contribution are also recognized by friendly units."<ref name=zhang198>{{harvnb|Zhang|1995|p=198}}.</ref>

A candidate for the medal would normally be nominated by the deputy [[political commissar|political officer]] of a company, while all squads within the company were required to meet once a month to list each soldier's accomplishments for the selection process.<ref name=zhang197_198>{{harvnb|Zhang|1995|pp=197&ndash;198}}.</ref> Once nominated, the PLA [[General Political Department]] or the candidate's [[PLA Military Region|military region]] political department would be responsible for approving the nomination.<ref name=regulation>{{zh icon}}{{cite | url = http://news.xinhuanet.com/mil/2007-11/22/content_7126987_1.htm | title = People's Liberation Army Discipline Regulations Chapter Two: Awards (<U+4E2D><U+56FD><U+4EBA><U+6C11><U+89E3><U+653E><U+519B><U+7EAA><U+5F8B><U+6761><U+4EE4><U+7B2C><U+4E8C><U+7AE0><U+FF1A><U+5956><U+52B1>) | date = 2002-03-23 |publisher = Xinhua | location = Beijing, China| accessdate = 2010-10-06}}</ref>

==Reward and regulation==

Once the nomination is approved, the recipient would be treated with a grand prize-giving ceremony that is intended to educate the entire PLA or the recipient's military region.<ref name=regulation/><ref name=zhang198_199>{{harvnb|Zhang|1995|pp=198, 199}}.</ref> Besides the medal, the recipient also receives a [[ribbon bar]] and a certificate from the PLA General Political Department.<ref name=xinhua/> According to the 1988 regulation, the medal must be worn on the upper left side of the recipient's uniform. The regulation also decreed that the medal itself can only be worn during special meetings and celebrations, while the ribbon bars are allowed in daily functions.<ref name=xinhua/>

